<h1 class="title"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111203044840/http://www.evbogue.com/">Ev Bogue</h1></a>


<div class="posts">


<h2 id="post-324"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111203044840/http://evbogue.com/farbeyondthestars/" rel="bookmark">Far Beyond The Stars</a></h2>
<div class="entry">
	<p><strong><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111203044840/http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5146/5669435687_646000fe55_o.jpg"><img class="alignright" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20111203044840im_/http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5146/5669435687_646000fe55_o.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300"/></a>What was Far Beyond The Stars?</strong></p>
<p>Far Beyond The Stars was a blog that I launched in October of 2009 and deleted in February of 2011. It was about minimalism, location independence, and working for yourself. I wrote it as I relocated a number of times around America during the timeframe with all of my stuff in a bag.</p>
<p><strong>Why did you launch Far Beyond The Stars?</strong></p>
<p>At the end of 2009, I was unemployed and my funds were running low. I&#8217;d moved to Portland Oregon at the end of August with all of my stuff in a bag and $3,000 in the bank. I wasn&#8217;t sure what I was going to do once I got there, I just knew that I had to get out of New York.</p>
<p>I tried a lot of things during that time. I attempted to reinvigorate my photography business, I applied for jobs, I redesigned some websites for people. One of the things I tried was launching a new blog. I&#8217;d been blogging on and off for years at Evbogue.com, but that blog had been mostly about my college experience &#8212; which I&#8217;d left far behind by 2009 (I graduated from NYU in 2006). So, I launched a new blog: Far Beyond The Stars.</p>
<p>I began writing about my experiences living without many physical possessions. I had around 97 things at launch time and bottomed out at 47 when I moved to Oakland in May 2010.</p>
<p>I wrote about how I quit my job, and how I hoped to not have to get another one. Pretty quickly a huge group of people started following the blog. By the end of 2009 I was getting 40,000 uniques a month, and just over 1,000 subscribers. By the middle of 2010, I topped out at 80,000 uniques and 8,700 subscribers.</p>
<p><strong>Where did the name come from?</strong></p>
<p>Far Beyond The Stars was the title a Star Trek: Deep Space Nine episode about a magazine writer in the 1940s who writes science fiction. I registered the domain name while I was in high school or early in college and pulled it out years later for the blog. I still own the domain, but it&#8217;s currently forwarding to Evbogue.com.</p>
<p>The title had nothing to do with the topic I was writing about. This gave me the freedom to write about whatever I wanted to, instead of being stuck on a specific topic.</p>
<p><strong>Why did Far Beyond The Stars become so popular?</strong></p>
<p>I wrote about living in a better way, and told my story from experience. People connected with the idea, and helped it spread. Far Beyond The Stars was one of the first blogs writing about minimalism as a solution to many of the problems facing Americans during the late 2000s, post-recession.</p>
<p>I simply said: look, I&#8217;m living with less than 100 things. I can move wherever I want, because everything I own fits into a backpack. I quit my day job, but it&#8217;s not a huge deal. Why? Because my overhead is incredibly low.</p>
<p><strong>How do you make an income from your blog?</strong></p>
<p>All of my income from the year of 2010, which ended up being in the high 5-digits, came from <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111203044840/http://www.evbogue.com/books">e-book</a> sales from Far Beyond The Stars.</p>
<p><strong>What did you learn from the year and a half that you published at Far Beyond The Stars?</strong></p>
<p>I learned that every time I slipped into hypotheticals and hype, I was clouding the message. The work that people connected to most was when I was talking about my actual experience of the world.</p>
<p>For example: I could have blogged about how it would be nice to live with 97 things, then I&#8217;d be able to quit my day job.<br/>
Instead: I blogged about living with less than 97 things, after I quit my day job.</p>
<p>By telling from experience a compelling story about myself and how I lived in the world, many people became interested in supporting the journey.</p>
<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111203044840/http://www.farbeyondthestarsthearchives.com/">Far Beyond The Stars is archived here</a> as a blog.</p>
<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111203044840/http://fbts.michaelxander.de/">Far Beyond The Stars is archived here</a> as PDFs.</p>

   </div>
